and":"Lancashire, England","Tunstall, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Tunstall, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud was born in 1252, in Tunstall, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 3 sons and 4 daughters with John de Tunstall. She died about 1302, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1252–Abt 1302":"1252–umbes 1302","1238–1302":"1238–1302","1268–1315":"1268–1315","1273–1292":"1273–1292","1273–1337":"1273–1337","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1278–Female":"1278–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1252–1302":"1252–1302","about 1282":"umbes 1282","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1252":"1252","Abt 1302":"umbes 1302","1273":"1273","1282":"1282","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1238":"1238","1302":"1302","1268":"1268","ABT 1276":"umbes 1276","1278":"1278","1